WEBVTT

00:18.760 --> 00:25.520
[Indistinct talking]

00:27.880 --> 00:32.080
[Car engines running]

00:33.120 --> 00:35.680
[Subtle beeping]

00:35.800 --> 00:36.960
- [Man Off Camera]: Are you
guys going to stop ever,

00:37.000 --> 00:38.720
or are you gonna
keep dancing forever?

00:38.760 --> 00:40.560
- I'm gonna keep dancing
forever, I mean.

00:40.600 --> 00:41.720
Well, at least 'til
I remember

00:41.760 --> 00:42.840
where I put my car.

00:42.880 --> 00:47.560
[Rhythmic electronic beeping]

00:47.600 --> 00:49.200
- [Female Narrator]: This
is the story of women

00:49.240 --> 00:52.040
who hear music
in their heads,

00:52.960 --> 00:54.960
of radical sounds

00:55.000 --> 00:57.720
where there was once silence,

00:58.880 --> 01:02.120
of dreams enabled
by technology.

01:07.000 --> 01:10.440
- Technology is a
tremendous liberator.

01:10.960 --> 01:12.920
It blows up power structures.

01:12.960 --> 01:15.000
[Rhythmic electronic beeping
becoming more complex]

01:15.280 --> 01:19.120
Women are naturally drawn
to electronic music.

01:20.800 --> 01:22.160
You didn't have
to be accepted

01:22.200 --> 01:25.160
by any of the
male-dominated resources:

01:25.200 --> 01:26.080
the radio stations,

01:26.120 --> 01:27.280
the record companies,

01:27.320 --> 01:28.760
the concert hall venues,

01:28.800 --> 01:31.960
the funding organisations.

01:33.360 --> 01:35.560
You could make something
with electronics

01:35.600 --> 01:39.680
and you can present music
directly to your audience

01:39.720 --> 01:43.480
and that gives you
tremendous freedom.

01:44.600 --> 01:47.640
But somehow women get
forgotten from that history.

01:47.760 --> 01:50.480
[Electronic beeping darkens
and fades away]

01:50.920 --> 01:52.040
- [Female Narrator]: The
history of women

01:52.080 --> 01:54.480
has been a
story of silence,

01:54.520 --> 01:56.560
of breaking through
the silence.

01:56.600 --> 02:00.480
- We shall not be
robbed any longer.

02:00.600 --> 02:03.280
- [Female Narrator]:
With beautiful noise

02:03.400 --> 02:05.840
[Rhythmic electronic beeping]

02:05.960 --> 02:10.200
[Beeping merges into
a stagnant tone]

02:17.160 --> 02:19.840
- This is April 30th, 1974.

02:19.880 --> 02:21.800
And we're all here at
the Bonino Gallery.

02:21.840 --> 02:23.240
- [Woman Off Camera]:
What's your name?

02:23.280 --> 02:26.600
- Suzanne Ciani,
C-I-A-N-I.

02:26.640 --> 02:27.680
[Giggles]

02:27.720 --> 02:28.840
[Subdued electronic music]

02:28.880 --> 02:30.160
And I'm going to give...

02:30.200 --> 02:34.320
I'm going to play a concert
on the Buchla synthesizer.

02:35.560 --> 02:38.440
These instruments are
designed by a manufacturer

02:38.480 --> 02:41.160
in Berkeley, California.

02:41.200 --> 02:44.160
They're probably the most
sophisticated system

02:44.200 --> 02:46.560
that's available.

02:46.600 --> 02:48.160
And I think they're sensual.

02:48.200 --> 02:49.200
May I have a cigarette?

02:49.240 --> 02:50.080
- [Woman Off Camera]:
They're what?

02:50.120 --> 02:51.920
- Sensual.

02:51.960 --> 02:53.160
Thank you.

02:59.200 --> 03:03.160
With this new technology,
you could do it all yourself.

03:03.200 --> 03:04.480
So you were the composer.

03:04.520 --> 03:07.800
you were the performer,
you were the sole arbiter

03:07.840 --> 03:09.480
of your creation.

03:09.520 --> 03:29.200
[Haunting synthesizer music]

03:29.240 --> 03:43.160
[Repetitive melodic tones layer
over prolonged swelling tones]

03:43.200 --> 03:45.800
And the machine was alive.

03:45.840 --> 03:47.680
It was warm.

03:47.720 --> 03:50.040
It communicated.

03:50.080 --> 03:51.520
It was sensitive.

03:51.560 --> 03:53.280
You know, you could
move something

03:53.320 --> 03:55.920
just the littlest bit

03:55.960 --> 03:59.320
and then a whole new
expression would open up.

03:59.360 --> 04:13.840
[Synthesizer music deepens
and intensifies]

04:13.880 --> 04:22.840
[Deep, full tones move quickly
as swelling tones continue]

04:22.880 --> 04:26.080
One of the most amazing
experiences you can have

04:26.200 --> 04:29.400
is to be in the middle of
this sound that's moving.

04:34.200 --> 04:37.200
The thing that I've always
loved about electronic music

04:37.240 --> 04:39.200
is that it's in motion.

04:39.240 --> 04:42.960
It's malleable.

04:43.000 --> 04:47.360
It's a much more open
set of dynamics.

04:47.400 --> 04:57.680
[A new melody emerges
as lower tones steady]

04:57.720 --> 05:01.200
In electronics, you're not
dealing so literally with

05:01.240 --> 05:04.000
the architecture of
nodes or harmonies,

05:04.040 --> 05:09.200
those building blocks
in classical music.

05:09.560 --> 05:11.040
You're dealing in energy.

05:11.080 --> 05:13.680
[Air whooshing]

05:13.720 --> 05:20.680
[Synthesizer music
becomes more hurried]

05:21.160 --> 05:23.640
- [Female Narrator]: At the
dawn of the 20th century,

05:23.680 --> 05:26.240
the world was
no longer silent.

05:28.880 --> 05:32.280
The spirit of modern
life was a banshee

05:32.320 --> 05:35.120
screeching into
the future.

05:37.640 --> 05:39.280
Futurists wanted to
make art out of

05:39.320 --> 05:43.120
the new energy,
speed, and noise.

05:44.600 --> 05:48.120
How would we begin
to do such a thing,

05:48.160 --> 05:52.920
to capture the sound of
this electrified world?

05:53.440 --> 06:01.600
[Humming pitch mirrors
Clara's hand movements]

06:01.640 --> 06:03.920
- I do very much what
a diver would do.

06:03.960 --> 06:06.600
I just have to take a chance.

06:06.640 --> 06:09.240
And here I am.

06:09.280 --> 06:11.160
[Hum jumps from a lower
octave to a higher octave]

06:11.200 --> 06:11.920
See?

06:11.960 --> 06:15.000
A hair breadth off and I'm
already on a different note.

06:16.120 --> 06:18.520
Dr. Ray, now
we'll have fun.

06:18.560 --> 06:19.160
[Dr. Ray laughs]

06:19.200 --> 06:20.480
Now we'll have fun.

06:20.520 --> 06:22.160
Now, here, hold
your hand over this.

06:22.200 --> 06:30.520
[Electronic tones whining in
tandem with hand movements]

06:30.560 --> 06:32.720
It is a fallacy to think
that the instrument

06:32.760 --> 06:34.240
is easy to play.

06:34.280 --> 06:37.320
It is much more difficult
than the violin.

06:37.360 --> 06:40.320
I was a concert violinist
before I played this.

06:40.360 --> 06:53.280
[Passionate classical music
on piano and Theremin]

06:53.320 --> 06:58.240
As young girls, both my sister
and I gave joint concerts

06:58.280 --> 07:02.240
playing the violin and the
piano all over Russia

07:02.280 --> 07:04.120
then all over Europe.

07:04.240 --> 07:06.080
We played our way to America.

07:14.880 --> 07:18.200
I met Professor Theremin
when he came to America

07:18.240 --> 07:20.320
to demonstrate the instrument.

07:20.360 --> 07:21.960
I was fascinated by

07:22.000 --> 07:24.560
the aesthetic part
of the instrument,

07:24.600 --> 07:25.280
the beauty,

07:25.400 --> 07:27.560
and the idea of
playing completely

07:27.600 --> 07:30.120
without touching anything.

07:30.160 --> 07:31.440
I also loved the sound of it.

07:31.480 --> 07:33.440
[Classical music continues]

07:33.480 --> 07:37.200
Professor Theremin became
a great friend and admirer,

07:37.240 --> 07:39.240
and we really worked on

07:39.280 --> 07:41.160
this particular
instrument together.

07:41.200 --> 07:44.560
I making my musical
pushes known to him,

07:44.600 --> 07:47.960
and he being the
genius that he was

07:48.000 --> 07:51.040
made it work.

07:51.080 --> 07:56.280
[Emotional
piano music]

07:56.320 --> 07:59.000
And we played the
Nardini Concerto.

07:59.040 --> 08:01.040
We played the whole
CÃ©sar Franck Sonata,

08:01.080 --> 08:04.240
which was at that time
a rather great surprise

08:04.280 --> 08:07.080
because the Theremin
was associated with

08:07.120 --> 08:08.760
just little melodies.

08:08.800 --> 08:14.160
[Theremin plays a deep,
passionate melody]

08:14.200 --> 08:16.000
- [Aura Satz]: Suddenly
you get someone

08:16.040 --> 08:17.680
who's a total virtuoso

08:17.720 --> 08:20.000
and able to make
it sound in a way

08:20.040 --> 08:22.520
that it had never
sounded before.

08:24.640 --> 08:36.320
[Mournful classical music
with piano accompaniment]

08:45.720 --> 08:47.240
- [Female Narrator]: You cannot
play air with hammers,

08:47.280 --> 08:50.000
Clara would say.

08:50.040 --> 08:52.280
You have to play with
butterfly wings.

08:52.320 --> 09:24.840
[Mournful classical
music continues]

09:25.360 --> 09:28.680
- [Clara Rockmore]: I was a
freak at the time.

09:28.720 --> 09:32.560
The public had to be won
over into thinking of it

09:32.600 --> 09:36.840
as a real artistic medium
played by an artist,

09:36.880 --> 09:39.200
and I won them over.

09:41.200 --> 09:47.400
[Birds chirping]

09:47.440 --> 09:49.720
A young composer
said to me,

09:49.760 --> 09:53.800
"It's listening to this
singing of a soul."

09:53.840 --> 09:55.760
Now isn't that
a lovely thought,

09:55.800 --> 09:58.680
singing of a soul?

09:58.840 --> 10:09.560
[Harsh, irregular tones]

10:09.680 --> 10:13.240
- The first stage in the
realisation of a piece of music

10:13.280 --> 10:15.240
is to construct the
individual sounds

10:15.280 --> 10:17.720
that we're going to use.

10:17.760 --> 10:19.720
To do this,
we go to these

10:19.760 --> 10:22.200
sound generators here,
electronic generators,

10:22.240 --> 10:25.480
and we listen to three of the
basic electronic sounds.

10:25.520 --> 10:27.320
First, is the simplest
sound of all,

10:27.360 --> 10:28.720
which is a sine wave.

10:28.760 --> 10:30.200
[Stagnant tone]

10:30.240 --> 10:31.200
You can see on
the oscilloscope,

10:31.240 --> 10:35.880
it has a very simple form and
has a very pure sound.

10:35.920 --> 10:38.160
Now listen to the same note
but with a different quality.

10:38.200 --> 10:40.440
This is a square wave.

10:40.480 --> 10:41.600
[Piercing stagnant tone]

10:41.640 --> 10:43.200
It's very square
on the picture

10:43.240 --> 10:44.840
and perhaps rather
harsh to listen to.

10:44.960 --> 10:46.800
This is because it has a lot
of high harmonics

10:46.840 --> 10:50.840
and that's what gives the
corners on the picture.

10:50.880 --> 10:55.160
Now a more complex
sound still is white noise.

10:55.200 --> 10:58.280
[Staticky, rain-like sound
with no distinguishable pitch]

10:58.320 --> 11:00.960
We don't always go to
electronic sound generators

11:01.000 --> 11:02.960
for our basic
sources of sound.

11:03.000 --> 11:06.760
If the sound we want exists
already in real life, say,

11:06.800 --> 11:08.320
we can go and record it.

11:08.360 --> 11:09.720
[Medium-pitched pop]

11:09.880 --> 11:12.400
[High-pitched, sharp tone]

11:12.520 --> 11:15.280
But those basic sounds
aren't really interesting

11:15.320 --> 11:17.000
in their raw
state like this.

11:17.040 --> 11:19.280
To make them of value
for a musical piece,

11:19.320 --> 11:22.760
we have to shape them
and mold them.

11:22.800 --> 11:24.400
We can get the lower sounds
we need from the rhythm

11:24.440 --> 11:26.760
by slowing down the tape.

11:26.800 --> 11:28.960
[Low-pitched pop]

11:29.000 --> 11:31.200
And the higher sounds by
speeding up the tape.

11:31.240 --> 11:32.880
[Pops get progressively
higher in pitch]

11:32.920 --> 11:34.520
And then all we have
to do is cut the notes

11:34.560 --> 11:37.120
to the right length.

11:37.160 --> 11:40.840
We can join them together on
a loop and listen to them.

11:40.880 --> 11:44.080
[Low pops become
rhythmic bass tones]

11:44.120 --> 11:47.960
And then with the higher
notes of the rhythm, again,

11:48.000 --> 11:49.760
we join them
together in a loop

11:49.800 --> 11:51.920
and play it in
synchronisation

11:51.960 --> 11:54.320
with the first tape.

11:54.360 --> 11:58.720
[Rapid rhythm of high "pop"
tones overlays bass tones]

11:58.760 --> 12:01.000
And over this we can play.

12:01.040 --> 12:06.080
[Rapid rhythm of higher
tones layers on top]

12:06.120 --> 12:11.160
[Mysterious melody begins]

12:11.200 --> 12:20.280
[Haunting ringing tones]

12:20.320 --> 12:22.760
Using all of these we can
build up any sound

12:22.800 --> 12:24.600
we can possibly
imagine.

12:24.640 --> 12:26.960
We spend quite a lot of time
trying to invent new sound,

12:27.000 --> 12:28.120
sounds that don't
exist already,

12:28.240 --> 12:29.960
sounds that can't be produced
by musical instruments.

12:30.000 --> 12:33.160
[Scratching]

12:33.280 --> 12:36.000
[High-pitched squeaking]

12:36.120 --> 12:39.240
The radio, the radio,
the radio was

12:39.280 --> 12:42.080
the most important
thing in my life.

12:42.120 --> 12:44.200
You know, there
weren't books.

12:44.240 --> 12:48.040
The radio was my education.

12:48.080 --> 12:51.040
[Haunting tones and
subdued beeping]

12:51.080 --> 12:55.080
I was accepted by the Oxford
and the Cambridge

12:55.120 --> 12:58.320
to read mathematics,
which is quite something

12:58.480 --> 13:01.800
for a working-class
girl in the '50s,

13:01.840 --> 13:07.080
where only one in 10
were female.

13:08.120 --> 13:11.800
- Delia was a
brilliant mathematician.

13:11.840 --> 13:15.160
She was fascinated by the
inner composition of a sound.

13:15.200 --> 13:17.480
Then she could reach
into it and decide

13:17.520 --> 13:21.160
what part of that sound
she wanted to use.

13:21.200 --> 13:23.800
[Distant sirens]

13:23.840 --> 13:30.280
[Menacing pulses]

13:30.320 --> 13:34.120
- [Delia Derbyshire]: I was in
Coventry during the Blitz.

13:34.160 --> 13:37.400
That was such an
influence on me.

13:41.440 --> 13:47.480
It's come to me that my love
for abstract sounds were

13:47.640 --> 13:50.200
sounds of the air raid siren.

13:50.240 --> 13:51.160
[Sirens continue]

13:51.280 --> 13:54.560
Because that's the sound you
hear and you don't know

13:54.600 --> 13:57.920
the source of it
as a young child.

13:57.960 --> 14:01.640
It's an abstract sound
and it's meaningful

14:01.760 --> 14:04.680
and then the all clear.

14:04.720 --> 14:09.400
[Sirens merge into electronic
music sounds]

14:13.000 --> 14:22.480
[Haunting hum]

14:27.040 --> 14:35.960
[Bombs exploding]

14:36.000 --> 14:38.560
- [Female Narrator]: World War II
emptied cities of men.

14:38.600 --> 14:40.680
[Time clock clicking]

14:40.720 --> 14:43.280
And in the absence of
men, women worked.

14:43.320 --> 14:45.400
[Machine rattling]

14:45.480 --> 14:48.400
Freedom was more
than a feeling.

14:52.800 --> 14:53.800
- [Man]: There isn't
much glamour

14:53.840 --> 14:55.600
about this
independence.

14:55.640 --> 14:57.560
Women at work are
getting to look and behave

14:57.600 --> 14:59.800
more like men.

14:59.840 --> 15:03.120
It's not very attractive.

15:05.360 --> 15:09.160
[Haunting squeaking sounds]

15:09.200 --> 15:12.280
- Welcome to Tower Folly,
this lonely host house

15:12.320 --> 15:15.280
on the North Downs of Kent.

15:15.320 --> 15:16.280
Well, as far
as I know

15:16.320 --> 15:18.000
this house isn't haunted
and there isn't

15:18.040 --> 15:20.240
a mad scientist in sight.

15:20.280 --> 15:23.240
This is in fact a music factory
where they can literally

15:23.280 --> 15:26.160
make music out of
electronic sounds,

15:26.200 --> 15:29.320
and the woman who makes it
has just been awarded a grant

15:29.360 --> 15:32.560
by the Gulbenkian Foundation
to help her research.

15:32.600 --> 15:34.520
She's here at
her control box,

15:34.560 --> 15:37.200
Miss Daphne Oram.

15:37.560 --> 15:40.040
How did you get involved
in this kind of work?

15:40.080 --> 15:42.960
- It dates back really
to 1944, I think,

15:43.000 --> 15:43.800
when I read a book

15:43.840 --> 15:46.600
which prophesied that
composers in the future

15:46.640 --> 15:48.560
would compose directly
into sound instead of

15:48.600 --> 15:50.960
using orchestral
instruments, you see.

15:51.000 --> 15:53.560
And well, since then
I've been working

15:53.600 --> 15:55.280
in BBC Studios,

15:55.320 --> 15:56.720
and so I've got
some little grasp

15:56.760 --> 15:58.720
of this sort of
equipment.

15:58.760 --> 16:01.560
[Upbeat orchestral
music starts]

16:01.600 --> 16:03.160
I was trained as a musician,

16:03.200 --> 16:06.760
and the two sort of
click together, you see.

16:08.840 --> 16:10.800
- Daphne was a
very gifted pianist

16:10.840 --> 16:13.200
and she had secured
a place for herself

16:13.240 --> 16:16.520
at the Royal Academy of Music,
which she turned down

16:16.560 --> 16:19.240
because she was also very
interested in technology

16:19.280 --> 16:22.280
and wanted to
work at the BBC.

16:22.320 --> 16:26.240
[Haunting electronic sounds]

16:26.280 --> 16:28.480
I was asked to do some
incidental music

16:28.520 --> 16:30.560
for a television play,

16:30.600 --> 16:34.280
and I did this by
getting together,

16:34.320 --> 16:35.720
in the middle of the night,

16:35.760 --> 16:39.240
all the tape recorders that
I could find in studios,

16:39.280 --> 16:41.280
collecting them together
in one studio,

16:41.320 --> 16:45.560
and working until they had to
be put back the next morning,

16:45.600 --> 16:47.240
sleeping a little bit and
then coming back in

16:47.280 --> 16:50.240
to do my normal
chamber music work.

16:50.280 --> 16:54.960
[Upbeat flute and piano
chamber music]

16:55.000 --> 16:57.520
Then it grew from that.

16:57.560 --> 17:01.160
I was asked to help start
the radiophonic workshop.

17:01.200 --> 17:04.520
- [Man Whispering]:
Listen.

17:04.560 --> 17:05.520
- Without Daphne,

17:05.560 --> 17:08.320
it would never have started
because BBC did not want

17:08.360 --> 17:10.280
an electronic music studio.

17:11.880 --> 17:14.800
We were just using anything
we could grab hold of.

17:14.840 --> 17:17.200
We had basic
laboratory equipment

17:17.240 --> 17:20.440
and a pair of tape machines
that had been liberated

17:20.480 --> 17:22.800
at the end of the war.

17:22.840 --> 17:25.200
[Banging and oscillating
electronic sounds]

17:25.240 --> 17:27.320
- Playwrights were
writing in a surreal

17:27.360 --> 17:28.800
kind of style,

17:28.840 --> 17:31.280
which was a
legacy of the war.

17:31.320 --> 17:34.800
The style required a
different kind of sound.

17:34.840 --> 17:37.800
- [echoing, haunting male voice]:
Bird or angel?

17:37.880 --> 17:39.840
- [Male Radio Announcer]: This
program is an experiment.

17:39.880 --> 17:41.200
We think it's
worth broadcasting

17:41.240 --> 17:43.080
as a perfectly serious
first attempt

17:43.120 --> 17:46.160
to find out whether
we can convey a new kind of

17:46.200 --> 17:49.000
emotional and
intellectual experience

17:49.040 --> 17:52.520
by means of what we call
radiophonic effects.

17:52.560 --> 17:55.960
[Trudging,
heavy beat]

17:56.000 --> 17:57.920
- [Echoing, rhythmic chanting]:
Round and round

17:57.960 --> 18:01.280
like a wind
from the ground.

18:01.320 --> 18:07.000
[Unintelligible]

18:07.120 --> 18:10.800
- [Male Radio Announcer]: It's
a sort of modern magic.

18:10.840 --> 18:14.520
Some musicians believe that
it can become an art form

18:14.560 --> 18:16.240
complete in itself.

18:16.280 --> 18:17.920
Others are skeptical.

18:17.960 --> 18:19.280
In fact, we've decided
not to use

18:19.320 --> 18:21.280
the word "music" at all.

18:21.320 --> 18:24.120
[Whispering and
howling sounds]

18:28.320 --> 18:30.240
- [Female Narrator]: What
began as a research trip

18:30.280 --> 18:36.520
to the Brussels World Fair
became a fateful pilgrimage.

18:36.640 --> 18:40.160
There, Daphne hears
an electronic composition

18:40.200 --> 18:41.840
fed through 350 speakers

18:41.880 --> 18:44.800
with synchronised
projections.

18:44.840 --> 18:47.760
[Low rumbling]

18:50.080 --> 18:54.240
Electronic music was more
than just incidental.

18:54.280 --> 18:58.480
It was the sound
of the future.

19:02.360 --> 19:04.800
- [Daphne Oram]: The radiophonic
workshop was concentrating

19:04.840 --> 19:07.440
somewhat on the drama side,

19:07.480 --> 19:10.000
and I wanted to concentrate
on the music side.

19:10.040 --> 19:16.280
So I set up my own studio.

19:16.320 --> 19:17.280
- She was a woman,

19:17.320 --> 19:19.200
in the 1950s,
set up her own

19:19.240 --> 19:21.680
independent electronic
music studio.

19:21.720 --> 19:23.480
It's extraordinarily brave.

19:23.520 --> 19:26.840
[Fluttering,
whistle-like sounds]

19:26.880 --> 19:27.840
- [Male Interiewer]:
Now Miss Oram,

19:27.880 --> 19:29.200
how do you go about
manufacturing

19:29.240 --> 19:30.680
this sort of sound?

19:30.720 --> 19:32.000
- Well, let me introduce

19:32.040 --> 19:34.160
this little electronic
generator here,

19:34.200 --> 19:36.200
which produces
a sound like this.

19:36.240 --> 19:38.360
[Resonant tone getting
progressively lower]

19:38.400 --> 19:40.760
Now I made a little
loop of tape here

19:40.800 --> 19:43.240
with varying pure
tones on it.

19:43.280 --> 19:45.240
[Rapidly ascending tones]

19:45.280 --> 19:48.720
Now if I then put a little
artificial reverberation

19:48.760 --> 19:50.360
on that,
I think you'll see

19:50.400 --> 19:52.160
we're just beginning
to get somewhere

19:52.200 --> 19:53.240
with the music.

19:53.280 --> 20:01.720
[Reverberating, ethereal
ascending tone patterns]

20:01.760 --> 20:09.800
[Simple melody playing]

20:12.080 --> 20:47.680
[Joyful melody plays over
percussive tapping]

20:47.720 --> 20:49.280
- [Male Interviewer]: What are
you going with this

20:49.320 --> 20:52.040
three-and-a-half thousand
pounds that you've got?

20:52.080 --> 20:53.720
- Well, this is very
exciting to me

20:53.760 --> 20:57.200
because I have ideas for a
piece of electronic equipment,

20:57.240 --> 20:58.360
not quite like this.

20:58.400 --> 21:00.480
In this case,
the composer,

21:00.520 --> 21:03.800
we're going to be able to
feed in drawn symbols

21:03.840 --> 21:07.840
straight into the equipment
and out will come the sounds.

21:07.880 --> 21:11.320
[Rumbling]

21:11.360 --> 21:14.200
I have a new
technique completely,

21:14.240 --> 21:17.800
one that I've evolved
over the years,

21:17.840 --> 21:20.480
which I call oramics.

21:20.520 --> 21:24.760
Now that is using graphic
representation of sound.

21:24.800 --> 21:27.240
[Reverberating tones]

21:27.280 --> 21:30.160
There seems to be
no real notation system

21:30.200 --> 21:31.680
in electronic music.

21:31.720 --> 21:35.760
I wanted a system where I
could graphically represent

21:35.800 --> 21:39.240
what I wanted and
give that representation,

21:39.280 --> 21:42.040
that musical score,
in fact, to a machine

21:42.080 --> 21:44.960
and have from it
the sound.

21:45.000 --> 21:51.320
[Reverberating tones
continue]

21:51.360 --> 21:55.720
[playful waltz of
electronic tones]

21:55.760 --> 21:57.440
- This idea of drawn sound

21:57.480 --> 22:00.040
is a sound that
comes from nowhere.

22:00.080 --> 22:04.200
It's a sound that is
synthesised from nothing,

22:04.240 --> 22:06.160
but she's not the
ghost in the machine

22:06.200 --> 22:08.160
her hands are
all over it.

22:08.200 --> 22:23.280
[playful waltz continues]

22:23.320 --> 22:26.960
- The composer wants to
project something of himself.

22:27.000 --> 22:31.240
The great works of art are a
projection of a human mind.

22:31.280 --> 22:35.240
And unless this machine can
accept and produce exactly

22:35.280 --> 22:38.200
this projection of the
composer's thought,

22:38.320 --> 22:41.560
then I think it's just a
machine and I can quite see

22:41.600 --> 22:44.000
why people can get
frightened at the thought.

22:46.120 --> 22:51.720
[Percussive beat resembling
a train on tracks]

22:51.760 --> 22:53.480
[Eliane Radigue speaking French]

22:58.280 --> 23:02.240
[Percussive beat continues]

23:18.200 --> 23:21.720
[Ocean-like waves of sound]

23:29.520 --> 23:33.520
[Airplane engine roaring]

23:41.280 --> 23:49.880
[Prolonged metallic tones]

24:16.400 --> 24:20.320
Pierre Schaeffer said, "In
between noise and music,

24:20.360 --> 24:22.920
"there is the hand
of the musician."

24:22.960 --> 24:25.080
[Man speaking French]

24:25.320 --> 24:27.520
[French voice recording
repeats on a loop]

24:27.560 --> 24:28.280
- Stop.

24:28.320 --> 24:32.440
[Eliane speaking French]

25:03.240 --> 25:15.240
[light chiming tones overlay
deep airy sounds]

25:15.360 --> 25:17.160
- [Female Narrator]: Eliane
dreamt of an unreal,

25:17.200 --> 25:22.960
impalpable music appearing
and fading away like clouds

25:23.000 --> 25:26.160
in the blue summer sky.

25:26.200 --> 25:47.320
[Slow pulses of pleasant
tones and chimes]

25:51.360 --> 25:54.120
[Eliane speaking French]

25:59.200 --> 26:01.040
[Mix of mysterious
electronic sounds]

26:01.320 --> 26:03.360
[Pierre Henry speaking French]

26:09.960 --> 26:11.280
[Eliane speaking French]

27:01.800 --> 27:25.840
[Single tone splits into
multiple dissonant tones]

27:25.880 --> 27:50.360
[A complex chorus
of tones emerges]

27:52.600 --> 27:55.920
- [Man]: Greenwich Village is
mostly a state of mind.

27:55.960 --> 27:57.760
[Blues music]

27:58.520 --> 28:01.200
- [Bebe Barron]: The Village
in the 50s had to be

28:01.240 --> 28:04.480
the most exciting, wonderful
place in the world.

28:04.520 --> 28:08.200
It was unbelievable,
like Paris in the 20s.

28:12.040 --> 28:17.800
We were married in '48 and
Louis's cousin brought us

28:17.840 --> 28:21.640
a tape recorder for
a wedding present.

28:21.680 --> 28:24.000
I think we were the
only ones in the country

28:24.040 --> 28:26.480
with that machine.

28:26.520 --> 28:30.160
We had all the artists in
The Village coming to us

28:30.200 --> 28:32.240
for recording work.

28:32.280 --> 28:34.440
[Reverberating high
and low tones]

28:34.480 --> 28:36.240
- [Female Performer]:
I remember my first

28:36.280 --> 28:38.520
birth in water.

28:38.560 --> 28:44.600
I sway and float,
stand on boneless toes,

28:44.640 --> 28:47.880
listening for
distant sounds,

28:47.920 --> 28:52.040
sounds beyond the
reach of human ears.

28:52.080 --> 28:55.320
[Whistling tones join the
reverberating tones]

28:55.360 --> 28:58.280
- [Bebe]: We started
a recording studio.

28:58.320 --> 29:02.080
We built almost all the
equipment ourselves

29:02.120 --> 29:04.320
because there
wasn't any to buy.

29:04.360 --> 29:05.320
[Upbeat orchestral music]

29:05.360 --> 29:07.200
- [Male Announcer]: The great
American boy is hard at work

29:07.240 --> 29:11.760
inventing, creating,
building something.

29:11.800 --> 29:14.760
And the desire to build
and create new things

29:14.800 --> 29:16.280
is the energy that develops

29:16.320 --> 29:21.760
industrious, dependable
citizens of tomorrow.

29:21.800 --> 29:23.760
- [Louis Barron]: It was
exciting because you were

29:23.800 --> 29:26.080
building these things and
you're experimenting with

29:26.120 --> 29:27.160
the electronic media.

29:27.200 --> 29:30.160
[Bubbling sounds dance
atop an asymmetrical beat]

29:30.200 --> 29:31.640
- [Female Narrator]:
Louis made sounds

29:31.680 --> 29:34.320
by overloading circuit boards,

29:34.360 --> 29:39.320
which Bebe then processed and
manipulated to create music.

29:39.360 --> 29:40.920
To the writer,
AnaÃ¯s Nin,

29:40.960 --> 29:47.120
it sounded like a molecule
had stubbed its toe.

29:47.160 --> 29:51.200
- [Bebe]: And we started
working on avant-garde films.

29:51.240 --> 29:53.160
That's what this
was all about,

29:53.200 --> 29:54.840
was the avant-garde.

30:00.280 --> 30:06.480
[Mysterious,
space-like music]

30:06.600 --> 30:10.440
The sense of wonder and awe,

30:10.480 --> 30:12.280
the beauty coming
from the circuits.

30:12.320 --> 30:17.280
I mean we would just sit back
and let them take over.

30:18.400 --> 30:27.600
[Deep roars and descending,
spinning tones]

30:27.640 --> 30:31.280
- [Louis]: These circuits
are not instruments.

30:31.320 --> 30:33.960
They are performance.

30:34.000 --> 30:35.320
- [Bebe]: We would record

30:35.360 --> 30:39.280
everything that
came out of the circuits.

30:39.320 --> 30:42.200
I spent hours and
hours and hours

30:42.240 --> 30:43.680
listening to all that stuff.

30:43.720 --> 30:44.560
- [Louis]: Oh yeah.

30:44.600 --> 30:46.200
Well, later you
went through-

30:46.240 --> 30:47.200
- [Bebe]: Days!

30:47.240 --> 30:49.000
- [Louis]: Miles of tape.
- [Bebe]: Yeah.

30:49.040 --> 30:52.320
- [Louis]: Incredible, and she could
hold it in her memory.

30:52.360 --> 30:55.560
She could remember where to
go for a certain feeling

30:55.600 --> 30:57.680
in the sound.

30:57.720 --> 30:59.960
[Sounds resembling sirens]

31:00.000 --> 31:03.160
- Bebe had a formal
musical education.

31:03.200 --> 31:06.160
She made most of the
compositional decisions

31:06.200 --> 31:12.440
while Louis dealt more with
the technical side of things.

31:12.760 --> 31:15.160
The Barrons'
greatest achievement

31:15.200 --> 31:17.920
was with the music for
Forbidden Planet.

31:17.960 --> 31:19.080
[Spinning high-pitched tones]

31:19.120 --> 31:23.080
It was the first movie with
an all-electronic score.

31:23.120 --> 31:26.080
[Whale-like moaning]

31:26.320 --> 31:30.080
- The pride and joy of
that period was in coming up

31:30.120 --> 31:32.360
with the music
for the monster.

31:32.400 --> 31:36.200
[Descending, spinning tone
meets an ascending moan]

31:36.240 --> 31:38.880
We were just
beside ourselves.

31:38.920 --> 31:42.680
Suddenly, this circuit
started generating

31:42.720 --> 31:47.560
the most complex sounds.

31:47.600 --> 31:53.920
The dying of Morbius was the
actual dying of the circuit.

31:53.960 --> 31:55.920
[Deep moaning]

31:55.960 --> 32:02.000
[Harsh, distressed
screeching]

32:02.040 --> 32:14.280
[Screeching getting
higher and higher]

32:14.320 --> 32:19.520
[Tones descend into silence]

32:19.560 --> 32:25.760
[Bubbling sounds]

32:25.800 --> 32:27.600
- [Louis]: We would
have a credit that said,

32:27.640 --> 32:31.240
"Electronic music by
Louis and Bebe Barron."

32:31.280 --> 32:33.960
But a memo was circulated
among the executives.

32:34.000 --> 32:36.240
How would the American
Federation of Musicians

32:36.280 --> 32:40.560
respond to a credit that
says electronic music?

32:41.840 --> 32:44.160
- The Musicians' Union would not

32:44.200 --> 32:49.000
allow the soundtrack
to be considered music.

32:49.040 --> 32:51.520
[Haunting, spinning tones
sprinkled with bubbling sounds]

32:51.560 --> 32:54.320
They were afraid that someday
their jobs would be replaced

32:54.360 --> 32:57.920
by machines and so they
would have none of it.

32:58.760 --> 33:02.560
That's why it's credited
as "electronic tonalities."

33:02.600 --> 33:07.200
[Deep, haunting sounds]

33:07.240 --> 33:09.920
- [Bebe]: It was so awful.

33:09.960 --> 33:16.480
We were barely
acknowledged as composers.

33:16.520 --> 33:19.280
[Harsh, metallic
swell of sound]

33:19.320 --> 33:22.480
[Rhythmic,
determined melody]

33:25.880 --> 33:32.480
[Sweeping whoosh of air]

33:32.520 --> 33:42.360
[Mysterious space-like
melody]

33:42.760 --> 33:44.280
- Prior to Dr. Who,

33:44.320 --> 33:49.280
there's a lot of distaste
of electronic music.

33:49.320 --> 33:52.280
Delia's music is
absolutely crucial

33:52.320 --> 33:54.760
in changing
that perception.

33:54.800 --> 33:56.440
[Mysterious,
reverberating tones]

33:56.480 --> 33:59.000
- [Woman]: It's like a
lighthouse, isn't it?

33:59.040 --> 34:01.160
I wonder what it's like up
there in a thunderstorm.

34:01.200 --> 34:03.760
Think of being up there
on a starry night,

34:03.800 --> 34:06.240
with all the world
at your feet.

34:06.280 --> 34:08.280
- You get people
who are writing in

34:08.320 --> 34:09.320
saying, "What is this?"

34:09.360 --> 34:11.320
"How is it made?"

34:11.360 --> 34:13.720
- Imagine what life must
have been like

34:13.760 --> 34:16.040
before samplers,
before synthesizers,

34:16.080 --> 34:18.760
before sequencers?

34:18.800 --> 34:21.280
It took her 40 days to make
the Doctor Who theme.

34:21.320 --> 34:23.720
40 days.

34:27.240 --> 34:30.240
- She would sample
a green lamp shade,

34:30.280 --> 34:33.240
speed it up,
reverse it,

34:33.280 --> 34:36.200
and just completely changed
the nature of the sound.

34:36.240 --> 34:38.520
[Bell chiming]

34:38.560 --> 34:41.520
[Sustained,
warm bell tones]

34:41.560 --> 34:45.520
[Birds chirping]

34:45.560 --> 34:47.840
- This was a
documentary program

34:47.880 --> 34:52.000
about the Tuareg tribe,

34:52.040 --> 34:57.160
the Tuareg tribe of nomads
in the Sahara desert.

34:57.200 --> 35:00.560
In the piece,
I tried to convey

35:00.600 --> 35:06.280
the distance of the horizon
and the heat haze,

35:06.320 --> 35:11.280
the strand of camels
wandering across the desert.

35:11.320 --> 35:14.200
That, in fact, was made
from square waves

35:14.240 --> 35:18.280
put through every filter
I could possibly find.

35:18.320 --> 35:35.280
[Harsh sustained tones over
warm, swelling bell tones]

35:37.520 --> 35:40.240
- [Barry performing]:
There must be a god.

35:40.800 --> 35:41.560
Oh, yes.

35:41.600 --> 35:49.160
[Ethereal, layered
choral chanting]

35:49.200 --> 35:51.280
Delia Derbyshire created

35:51.320 --> 35:53.200
some very, very
beautiful things

35:53.240 --> 35:54.160
and some things that had

35:54.200 --> 35:56.440
a very strange and
unearthly quality

35:56.480 --> 35:59.680
that couldn't quite be got, I think,
by normal musical means

35:59.720 --> 36:01.360
and yet didn't
sound as if

36:01.400 --> 36:03.360
they were electronically
manufactured.

36:03.400 --> 36:09.920
[Ethereal choral
chanting continues]

36:09.960 --> 36:14.520
- Some of it was
worked out mathematically.

36:14.560 --> 36:16.320
[Repeated beeping tones]

36:16.360 --> 36:18.320
I've tried to get into it

36:18.360 --> 36:24.720
a feeling of simplicity
and loneliness,

36:24.760 --> 36:26.720
of a man on a moon.

36:26.760 --> 36:37.240
[Ethereal,
sliding melody]

36:37.280 --> 36:39.960
- [Neil Armstrong]: That's
one small step for man,

36:41.080 --> 36:45.320
one giant leap
for mankind.

36:48.160 --> 36:49.840
- [Mandy]: She created
a kind of pathway

36:49.880 --> 36:52.240
for electronic music.

36:52.280 --> 36:53.520
- [Delia]: I did all
sorts of things

36:53.560 --> 36:55.560
I was told I couldn't do.

36:55.600 --> 37:00.760
I think I've always been a
very independent thinker.

37:04.200 --> 37:05.560
[Ethereal, sliding
melody ends]

37:05.600 --> 37:08.560
[Bomb exploding]

37:08.600 --> 37:23.960
[Rumbling sound
expands, then fades]

37:24.000 --> 37:25.280
- [Female Narrator]: While
the work of women

37:25.320 --> 37:27.240
like Delia and Daphne

37:27.280 --> 37:30.040
came from the deafening
sounds of wartime,

37:30.080 --> 37:33.200
it was the chilling silence
of the Cold War

37:33.240 --> 37:40.200
that took others to
the limits of listening.

37:40.240 --> 37:42.240
- The bomb scare psychology

37:42.280 --> 37:44.160
that was inculcated,

37:44.200 --> 37:46.240
that had a big
effect on the artists

37:46.280 --> 37:48.600
that were emerging
at that time.

37:48.640 --> 37:53.720
[Upbeat guitar music]

37:53.760 --> 37:57.240
Everybody was pushing
for opening things up,

37:57.280 --> 38:00.480
a kind of way through
all the terrible stuff

38:00.520 --> 38:02.200
that was going on in
the world at the time.

38:02.240 --> 38:04.480
So there was a lot of
political motivation behind

38:04.520 --> 38:05.800
what we were doing.

38:05.840 --> 38:06.800
- [Protestors] Peace now!

38:06.840 --> 38:09.000
Peace now!
Peace now!

38:09.040 --> 38:11.280
[Crowd cheering]

38:12.280 --> 38:13.480
- [David Rosenboom]: The
effect was to say,

38:13.520 --> 38:16.800
okay, we've got
to break through

38:16.840 --> 38:20.000
anything that was rigid,
anything that was limiting,

38:20.040 --> 38:22.680
and try to move
things forward.

38:22.720 --> 38:30.160
[Space-like, harsh,
high-pitched tones]

38:30.200 --> 38:31.600
- The music scene

38:31.640 --> 38:35.280
was evolving into
an area that was

38:35.320 --> 38:38.760
very fresh and exciting.

38:38.800 --> 38:42.800
[Screaming,
elongated tones]

38:42.840 --> 38:45.200
First time I heard
live electronic music

38:45.240 --> 38:47.160
was early '60s.

38:47.200 --> 38:50.200
Pauline was on stage
with an accordion.

38:50.240 --> 38:53.160
The room was exploding with a
sound that was ear-splitting.

38:53.200 --> 38:57.680
I had never experienced
that kind of volume before.

38:57.720 --> 39:11.160
[Piercing, screaming tones
ascending and descending]

39:11.200 --> 39:11.960
- [Pauline Oliveros]:
I can't remember

39:12.000 --> 39:15.160
when I wasn't
interested in sounds.

39:15.200 --> 39:19.920
I remember particularly
things like riding in the car

39:19.960 --> 39:23.000
with my parents for instance,
maybe in the backseat,

39:23.040 --> 39:25.280
listening to the sound
of the motor

39:25.320 --> 39:28.680
and listening to the sound
of my parents' voices

39:28.720 --> 39:30.280
being modulated by the motor.

39:30.320 --> 39:33.680
[Muffled conversation]

39:33.720 --> 39:36.680
Listening to my father
turn his shortwave radio,

39:36.720 --> 39:40.160
listening to the whistles
and pops and static.

39:40.200 --> 39:41.800
I mean, I was
always fascinated with

39:41.840 --> 39:44.800
the in-between sounds
in the stations,

39:44.840 --> 39:46.160
just tuning in between.

39:46.200 --> 39:47.440
I loved that.

39:47.480 --> 39:51.320
[Radio tuning]

39:51.360 --> 39:54.320
I credit my mother.

39:54.360 --> 39:56.160
For my birthday, she
sent me a tape recorder,

39:56.200 --> 39:58.800
and that was a very
significant event

39:58.840 --> 40:01.440
because nobody had
tape recorders, you know.

40:01.480 --> 40:03.160
It was in the 50s.

40:03.200 --> 40:09.480
[Relaxed, marching
dance music]

40:09.520 --> 40:13.800
I began to do field recording
from my apartment window.

40:13.840 --> 40:17.720
[High-pitched screeching tones
Trolley bell ringing]

40:17.760 --> 40:21.320
And then in 1959
got started making

40:21.360 --> 40:24.040
a tape piece called
Time Perspectives.

40:24.080 --> 40:25.240
[Wind chimes ringing]

40:27.120 --> 40:38.280
[Hollow object sliding
on a surface]

40:38.320 --> 40:41.200
The tape recorder that I had,
it was possible to record

40:41.240 --> 40:45.280
by hand winding the
tape in record mode.

40:45.320 --> 40:47.440
That gave me a variable
speed so I could do

40:47.480 --> 40:49.440
some interesting
things with that.

40:49.480 --> 40:51.280
[Bells continue ringing]

40:51.320 --> 40:54.200
[Sounds resembling
birds cawing]

40:54.240 --> 40:57.360
And I used the bathtub for
reverberation [chuckles]

40:57.400 --> 41:01.760
and cardboard tubes as filters.

41:01.800 --> 41:04.320
I'd put microphones in the
tube and then record sounds

41:04.360 --> 41:05.720
through the tube.

41:05.760 --> 41:13.040
[Hollow sound of
water gurgling]

41:13.080 --> 41:17.280
[Airy wash of sound]

41:19.280 --> 41:21.160
[Sustained accordion chord]

41:21.200 --> 41:23.320
[Object dropping]

41:28.000 --> 41:30.240
Eventually, I met up
with a group of people

41:30.280 --> 41:32.280
who were interested
in new music,

41:32.320 --> 41:34.520
[Haunting,
avant-garde music]

41:34.560 --> 41:36.200
which led to
the founding of

41:36.240 --> 41:39.280
the San Francisco
Tape Music Center.

41:42.280 --> 41:44.080
- The San Francisco
Tape Music Center

41:44.120 --> 41:47.160
was not associated
with an institution.

41:47.200 --> 41:50.240
So it was friends brought
together what equipment

41:50.280 --> 41:53.200
they had to share.

41:55.240 --> 41:57.240
- Our sense of what
we were doing

41:57.280 --> 42:01.360
at that point was opening
a place where poets,

42:01.400 --> 42:06.080
painters, film, and
electronic or tape music,

42:06.120 --> 42:07.360
where all this stuff
could be done.

42:07.400 --> 42:09.720
[Echoing,
haunting sounds]

42:09.760 --> 42:11.520
It was a sense
of individuality.

42:11.560 --> 42:13.840
Nobody wanted to
be like anyone else

42:13.880 --> 42:16.080
and everybody was
very supportive

42:16.120 --> 42:19.200
of what everybody
else was doing.

42:22.360 --> 42:25.760
- My interest was always
in live performance

42:25.800 --> 42:29.280
and I started to find out
ways to use tape recorders

42:29.320 --> 42:33.160
and perform live with them,
and that was making

42:33.200 --> 42:35.280
a tape delay system,
which allows me

42:35.320 --> 42:38.760
to maintain that physical
contact with the sound.

42:38.800 --> 42:42.280
[Screeching,
high-pitched tone]

42:42.520 --> 43:19.520
[Classical choral music
begins as tone continues]

43:19.880 --> 43:21.520
- [Female Narrator]: How do
you exercise the canon of

43:21.560 --> 43:25.760
classical music of misogyny

43:25.800 --> 43:29.800
with two oscillators,
a turntable, and tape delay?

43:34.360 --> 43:35.800
- Feminism was at the center

43:35.840 --> 43:36.760
of what she was doing,

43:36.800 --> 43:39.360
and it's strange because it
seems like if the boys' club

43:39.400 --> 43:42.200
is going to pick a token
woman, you would not pick

43:42.240 --> 43:45.320
a woman who is
that outspoken.

43:45.360 --> 43:48.600
[Drone-like tone]

43:48.840 --> 43:50.760
- Pauline was conscious
of the fact that

43:50.800 --> 43:52.280
she was different.

43:52.320 --> 43:55.200
She had a streak of
a revolutionary in her.

43:59.200 --> 44:00.920
- Pauline, it was hard,
you know,

44:00.960 --> 44:02.240
she had come
out in the 50s

44:02.280 --> 44:06.200
and here she was
a woman, gay,

44:06.240 --> 44:08.240
avant-garde music,

44:08.280 --> 44:10.720
each thing by itself
would be hard,

44:10.760 --> 44:12.440
but she had three
things that were hard

44:12.480 --> 44:13.840
and women composers

44:13.880 --> 44:15.920
were not being
performed, you know.

44:15.960 --> 44:22.160
[Choral voices emerge
over the drone-like tone]

44:22.200 --> 44:23.520
- [Male Interviewer]: You
wrote an editorial

44:23.560 --> 44:25.240
to the New York Times
once called

44:25.280 --> 44:26.440
"Don't Call Them
'Lady' Composers"

44:26.480 --> 44:27.840
- [Pauline]: That's right.
- Tell us about

44:27.880 --> 44:29.760
when you wrote
that and why.

44:29.800 --> 44:32.440
- [Pauline]: I just want to be
introduced as a composer.

44:32.480 --> 44:35.160
That has caused me
to use that title

44:35.200 --> 44:37.160
and to start
to point out

44:37.200 --> 44:40.320
how hard it was for women
to be taken seriously

44:40.360 --> 44:43.160
as creators of music.

44:43.200 --> 45:11.240
[Drone-like and choral
tones continue]

45:11.280 --> 45:15.960
- [Female Narrator]: Go
out walking at night.

45:16.000 --> 45:22.200
Tread so quietly the bottoms
of your feet become ears.

45:22.240 --> 45:25.000
Working with an
all-women ensemble,

45:25.040 --> 45:27.200
instructions like these were
intended to encourage

45:27.240 --> 45:29.000
deep listening.

45:29.040 --> 45:35.280
[Drone-like tone continues]

45:35.320 --> 45:46.280
[Long tones
resembling brass]

45:46.320 --> 45:47.280
- [Pauline]: I was alarmed

45:47.320 --> 45:48.920
as many were,
of course,

45:48.960 --> 45:51.320
with the Vietnam War,

45:51.360 --> 45:55.040
and I began to seek some ways
of working with sound

45:55.080 --> 46:00.200
that I could discover more
of a kind of inner peace.

46:02.320 --> 46:10.240
[Drone-like and brass
tones continue]

46:10.280 --> 46:14.280
I found myself listening
to long sounds

46:14.320 --> 46:16.560
and becoming more
interested in

46:16.600 --> 46:18.840
what the sounds
did themselves

46:18.880 --> 46:22.480
than what I would
do with them.

46:22.520 --> 46:27.240
And as this work proceeded,

46:27.280 --> 46:31.200
I began to become interested
in what the kind of listening

46:31.240 --> 46:38.160
I was doing did to me and my
own internal processes.

46:38.200 --> 46:42.760
[Drone-like tones continue]

46:42.800 --> 46:45.440
[Brass tones
sing gently]

46:45.480 --> 46:46.440
- [Female Interviewer]:
Does it have

46:46.480 --> 46:49.080
social and political
implications to you,

46:49.120 --> 46:50.600
the kind of music
that you write?

46:50.640 --> 46:52.040
- Oh, yes.

46:52.080 --> 46:57.440
Well, I feel that
one's interactions,

46:57.720 --> 47:01.760
the way one relates in an
organization of any kind,

47:01.800 --> 47:07.720
is political and social
and very important.

47:07.760 --> 47:11.360
The path that I hope to be on
is one where the energy

47:11.400 --> 47:16.600
that comes out of the work
that I do is beneficial

47:16.640 --> 47:18.320
to others as
well as myself.

47:18.360 --> 47:21.840
I want my work to be
mutually beneficial.

47:21.880 --> 47:23.240
I'm not interested in

47:23.280 --> 47:26.560
making an object of
art and entertainment.

47:26.600 --> 47:29.280
I'm interested in making
something that helps me

47:29.320 --> 47:32.800
to grow and expand and
change as an individual

47:33.960 --> 47:37.160
and in relation
to others.

47:37.200 --> 47:48.040
[Warm, layered
brass tones]

47:50.240 --> 47:52.000
- [Female Narrator]: Pauline's
preoccupation with

47:52.040 --> 47:53.200
how we hear and feel

47:53.240 --> 47:55.600
the sounds within
and around us

47:55.640 --> 47:59.280
were shared by
Maryanne Amacher at MIT,

47:59.320 --> 48:01.480
who was sounding
out the city.

48:01.520 --> 48:07.320
[Fluttering
high-pitched sounds]

48:07.360 --> 48:13.560
[Seagulls cawing]

48:13.600 --> 48:15.240
- I had installed a
microphone

48:15.280 --> 48:19.320
in eight locations at
the Boston Harbour

48:19.360 --> 48:22.240
in the New England
Fish Exchange

48:22.280 --> 48:26.200
connected to
telephone links.

48:28.360 --> 48:30.200
It was very nice to
come in late at night

48:30.240 --> 48:31.360
at 1:00 in the morning

48:31.400 --> 48:34.760
and just turn on the
mixer and have the sound

48:34.800 --> 48:38.720
coming from the distant
night when I liked it best

48:38.760 --> 48:41.360
because I could hear
patterns in various shapes.

48:41.400 --> 48:44.240
[Seagulls cawing]

48:44.280 --> 48:47.320
[Fluttering high-pitched
sounds continue]

48:47.360 --> 48:50.800
I realized, my, there's
a tone of this place.

48:50.840 --> 48:52.800
There's a whole undercurrent
that exists here

48:52.840 --> 48:57.200
that makes this
recognisable in some way.

48:57.240 --> 48:59.320
It wasn't hard to
analyse it in Boston.

48:59.360 --> 49:02.160
It was like a low F sharp.

49:02.200 --> 49:04.240
Then other places,
for example, New York,

49:04.280 --> 49:05.960
it was like a low E.

49:06.000 --> 49:10.960
[Subway train clattering]

49:11.000 --> 49:13.560
It wasn't that I wanted
the sounds of the birds

49:13.600 --> 49:16.480
or the sounds of the harbour
or any of these sounds,

49:16.520 --> 49:21.480
I really wanted to experience
and learn about hearing.

49:21.520 --> 49:26.040
[Pleasant harmony of tones]

49:26.080 --> 49:27.040
- [Male Interviewer]:
When people say to you,

49:27.080 --> 49:28.000
"Yeah, but is it music?"

49:28.040 --> 49:29.320
After you say,
"Yes it is,"

49:29.360 --> 49:31.160
how do you
expand on that?

49:31.200 --> 49:32.320
- [Maryanne]: Well,
I think that's sort of

49:32.360 --> 49:34.080
an old question
[chuckles].

49:34.120 --> 49:36.760
Much of our music, classical
pop, has this beat,

49:36.800 --> 49:39.280
has this gallop,
has this trot.

49:39.320 --> 49:44.480
I'm interested in music that
communicates some ideas,

49:46.480 --> 49:49.240
finding places where there is
space and dimension

49:49.280 --> 49:50.560
to the sound,

49:50.600 --> 49:54.000
sounds very very far away
and very close up.

49:54.040 --> 49:58.400
[Deep, airy sounds]

49:58.560 --> 50:00.840
- Maryanne was really
interested in

50:00.880 --> 50:02.520
contemporary science.

50:02.560 --> 50:05.200
She had been very interested
in muon research,

50:05.240 --> 50:08.360
these particles that speed
through the universe.

50:09.240 --> 50:12.200
- She was constantly
thinking about

50:12.240 --> 50:17.480
intersections of science,
life, and sound.

50:17.520 --> 50:22.800
[Airy and metallic,
droning sounds]

50:22.840 --> 50:24.720
- Her house
was incredible.

50:24.760 --> 50:29.760
It was in breathtakingly
bad condition.

50:29.800 --> 50:31.080
There was this
whole rack

50:31.120 --> 50:33.280
full of these sine
wave oscillators

50:33.320 --> 50:38.080
straight out of
a physics lab.

50:38.120 --> 50:39.320
And there's this
woman sitting there

50:39.360 --> 50:43.000
with this really intense,
buzzy energy.

50:43.040 --> 50:46.280
[Quivering metallic sounds]

50:46.320 --> 50:49.200
- She'd have a
rock-and-roll attitude

50:49.240 --> 50:51.280
towards, "I'm going to
make this whole house

50:51.320 --> 50:55.240
"vibrate and come alive."

50:55.280 --> 51:19.240
[Metallic sounds intensify
and rumble]

51:24.880 --> 51:28.160
- She wanted to
develop an extremely

51:28.200 --> 51:30.520
rigorous approach
to listening,

51:30.560 --> 51:32.840
[Low, constant tone
subtly shifting in quality]

51:32.880 --> 51:35.240
to activating sights,

51:35.280 --> 51:40.360
to thinking outside of
composition as it's known.

51:43.320 --> 51:44.960
She didn't want
to push around

51:45.000 --> 51:48.320
dead white men's notes.

51:54.320 --> 51:58.080
- I wanted to
create music where

51:58.120 --> 52:00.360
the listener actually had

52:00.400 --> 52:05.280
vivid experiences
of contributing.

52:05.800 --> 52:09.040
In composing, I am
conscious of the tones

52:09.080 --> 52:12.320
that you make in
response to the tones

52:12.360 --> 52:14.240
that a musician plays.

52:14.280 --> 52:19.280
[Subtle, harsh violin
string sounds]

52:19.320 --> 52:20.480
- One of the phenomenon
she was

52:20.520 --> 52:23.160
most interested in was
otoacoustic emission.

52:23.200 --> 52:26.560
She referred to
them as ear tones.

52:26.600 --> 52:29.280
If you have two frequencies
and they sound together,

52:29.320 --> 52:32.200
the ear and the mind try
to sort of resolve them.

52:32.240 --> 52:36.240
There is an emergent
third pitch.

52:37.240 --> 52:39.840
She can compose these outer
things that will produce

52:39.880 --> 52:40.960
this inner thing.

52:41.000 --> 52:43.440
[low, constant tone
subtly shifting in quality]

52:43.480 --> 52:44.280
She would refer to it as

52:44.320 --> 52:47.560
ghost writing the
listener's music.

52:51.080 --> 52:53.280
- The first time one
encounters her music

52:53.320 --> 52:55.920
and the way that it
dances inside your ear

52:55.960 --> 52:58.600
is this light bulb moment.

52:58.640 --> 53:00.280
You can actually play with

53:00.320 --> 53:03.280
the physicality
of the listener.

53:03.320 --> 53:09.000
[Soft, harsh violin
string sounds]

53:09.040 --> 53:11.280
[Low tone continues]

53:11.320 --> 53:17.720
[Tones are replaced by a
constant high-pitched tone]

53:17.760 --> 53:19.280
- Merce Cunningham commissioned

53:19.320 --> 53:21.680
a piece from her.

53:21.720 --> 53:22.680
[Sustained, chant-like tones]

53:22.720 --> 53:25.000
You'd hear this
very high pitch.

53:25.040 --> 53:27.280
[High pitch and
low tones continue]

53:27.320 --> 53:29.280
And then there
would be thunder,

53:29.320 --> 53:30.600
[Thunder rumbling softly]

53:30.640 --> 53:34.680
beautiful thunder recorded
in stereoscopic sound

53:34.720 --> 53:36.200
that would shift across
the room.

53:36.240 --> 53:41.240
[Thunder rumbles swell]

53:41.280 --> 53:44.440
And when it hit, there
would be this array

53:44.480 --> 53:47.320
of other frequencies
that would happen.

53:47.360 --> 53:49.760
It was very very beautiful.

53:49.800 --> 54:22.440
[High pitch continues as
thunder waxes and wanes]

54:22.480 --> 54:24.200
- [Female Narrator]:
The idea of

54:24.240 --> 54:26.360
a slowly-evolving composition

54:26.400 --> 54:28.360
that alters the listener

54:28.400 --> 54:32.800
also fired the imagination
of Eliane Radigue.

54:36.120 --> 54:41.680
[Grunt-like prolonged tone]

54:41.880 --> 54:43.560
[Eliane speaking French]

54:50.560 --> 54:55.240
[Varied electronic beeps]

55:03.400 --> 55:10.640
[Man singing to
an upbeat rhythm]

55:22.280 --> 55:23.160
- When I met Eliane,

55:23.200 --> 55:26.800
she had been working with
the Buchla synthesizer,

55:26.840 --> 55:29.800
yet this piece that
she wrote, Chry-ptus,

55:29.840 --> 55:34.200
sounded nothing
like a Buchla.

55:34.240 --> 55:38.840
[Spinning low tone]

55:38.880 --> 55:42.240
[High, piercing
pitch emerges]

55:42.280 --> 55:48.640
[Phone ringing sound]

55:49.080 --> 55:51.040
[Eliane speaking French]

55:56.320 --> 55:58.560
[Medium-pitched,
spinning tone]

56:17.640 --> 56:19.240
- We're talking
with Eliane Radigue

56:19.280 --> 56:21.600
who's here from Paris.

56:21.640 --> 56:23.280
Are you working with
both synthesisers

56:23.320 --> 56:25.560
and tape recording
processes?

56:25.600 --> 56:29.280
- [Eliane]: Yes,
the ARP synthesiser

56:29.320 --> 56:35.160
and the tape recorder.

56:35.200 --> 56:38.160
My main involvement with
music is to work on

56:38.200 --> 56:41.760
slow changing
of the sounds.

56:41.800 --> 56:42.440
- [Charles]: So in a way,

56:42.480 --> 56:44.360
you're working with time?

56:44.400 --> 56:47.320
- [Eliane]: Yes,
my last work, Adnos II,

56:47.360 --> 56:51.320
is 75 minutes long,
and it couldn't be shorter.

56:51.360 --> 56:54.440
It just goes like a stream.

56:54.480 --> 57:04.200
[Constant tone slightly
pulsates rhythmically]

57:04.240 --> 57:11.720
[A dissonant tone emerges]

57:11.760 --> 57:13.360
I should say that
this music I make

57:13.400 --> 57:14.760
is not so much welcome,

57:14.800 --> 57:17.440
except by a few
people, of course.

57:17.480 --> 57:19.160
There is nothing in between.

57:19.200 --> 57:21.560
People likes it,
or not at all.

57:21.600 --> 57:23.040
For the music establishment,

57:23.080 --> 57:25.320
they think that I
don't make music.

57:25.360 --> 57:27.520
That's not music.

57:27.560 --> 57:30.080
- [Charles] Oh, still arguing
about that, are we?

57:30.120 --> 57:32.520
[Eliane laughs]

57:33.200 --> 57:36.280
- Our music was meant
to be listened to

57:36.320 --> 57:38.320
in a different way than
how you'd listen to, like,

57:38.360 --> 57:41.160
a pop song.

57:41.200 --> 57:43.440
In a pop song
you're listening for

57:43.480 --> 57:45.800
melodies, harmonies, lyrics.

57:45.840 --> 57:48.440
In her music, you're
listening not just

57:48.480 --> 57:51.160
for the things that are
changing in the sound,

57:51.200 --> 57:53.160
but for the way
that the experience

57:53.200 --> 57:55.760
is changing your disposition.

57:55.800 --> 58:08.480
[Two main spinning tones]

58:08.520 --> 58:16.240
[Spinning gets more rapid]

58:16.280 --> 58:25.520
[Spinning slows, causing
the two tones to alternate]

58:32.120 --> 58:34.760
[Speaking French]

58:41.760 --> 58:43.800
[Man speaking French]

59:06.800 --> 59:08.680
[Dramatic whoosh of sound]

59:08.720 --> 59:19.160
[Baroque-like
electronic melody]

59:19.200 --> 59:21.360
[Man speaking French]

59:34.240 --> 59:37.520
[Piano notes playing]

59:37.560 --> 59:39.200
- [Wendy Carlos]: I'll
make it start very dull

59:39.240 --> 59:41.520
and then get very
bright like that.

59:41.560 --> 59:43.840
It sounds more like
a trumpet sound.

59:43.880 --> 59:49.160
[Brass-like synthesizer
notes playing]

59:49.240 --> 59:51.680
[Man speaking French]

59:55.320 --> 59:58.320
[Experimenting with
brass-like notes]

59:58.360 --> 1:00:00.280
And I'll add a little echo.

1:00:00.320 --> 1:00:01.560
[Brass-like notes become
more sustained]

1:00:01.600 --> 1:00:03.480
[Rapid baroque music]

1:00:03.520 --> 1:00:06.240
- The transgressive act of

1:00:06.280 --> 1:00:11.160
recontextualizing these classic
Western art music tropes,

1:00:11.200 --> 1:00:20.280
that takes a lot of strength,
humour, and vision.

1:00:20.320 --> 1:00:21.560
- [Suzanne]: Up until
that moment,

1:00:21.600 --> 1:00:23.560
electronic music
had this promise

1:00:23.600 --> 1:00:26.200
of a different vocabulary,
a different language,

1:00:26.240 --> 1:00:31.760
a new paradigm,
a new way of working.

1:00:31.800 --> 1:00:34.160
Switched-On Bach,
the way it impacted

1:00:34.200 --> 1:00:40.280
the public's consciousness
of what a synthesiser was,

1:00:40.320 --> 1:00:42.280
was completely retroactive.

1:00:42.320 --> 1:00:44.240
[Bach piece playing
on synthesizer]

1:00:44.280 --> 1:00:48.200
Everybody thought that
these things were about

1:00:48.240 --> 1:00:53.240
replicating sounds.

1:00:53.280 --> 1:00:58.320
To me, electronic music wasn't
about making baroque music

1:00:58.360 --> 1:01:00.320
with new timbres.

1:01:00.360 --> 1:01:05.200
It was a different
kind of music.

1:01:05.240 --> 1:01:08.160
You just had the
Summer of Love.

1:01:08.200 --> 1:01:13.200
Everything we knew
was being thrown out,

1:01:13.240 --> 1:01:15.240
and it was a whole new world.

1:01:15.280 --> 1:01:17.600
Electronics were
part of that world.

1:01:17.640 --> 1:01:18.960
[Ascending and descending
scales of electronic tones]

1:01:19.000 --> 1:01:19.280
- What are they?

1:01:19.320 --> 1:01:22.040
- Oh, these are
patch cords.

1:01:22.080 --> 1:01:24.320
These are the things
that route the signal

1:01:24.360 --> 1:01:27.160
from one little module to
another to get the sound.

1:01:27.200 --> 1:01:30.840
You can patch it a lot of
different ways and the way

1:01:30.880 --> 1:01:33.760
you patch it will
determine what you get.

1:01:33.800 --> 1:01:37.280
It's like creating
an instrument.

1:01:37.320 --> 1:01:38.280
- [Woman Off-Camera]: Do you
know before you put them in

1:01:38.320 --> 1:01:39.760
what it's going
to sound like?

1:01:39.800 --> 1:01:42.240
- Well, you're always
going towards an idea.

1:01:42.280 --> 1:01:46.080
That's what makes you put the
patch cords in certain places.

1:01:46.120 --> 1:01:48.240
- [Suzanne]: Part of an
instrument is what it can do

1:01:48.280 --> 1:01:50.840
and part of it is
what you do to it.

1:01:50.880 --> 1:01:53.200
The other part of music of
course is the motion

1:01:53.240 --> 1:01:56.200
and the personal involvement
that a musician gives

1:01:56.240 --> 1:01:57.200
to his instrument,

1:01:57.240 --> 1:01:59.160
and that's something
that I happen to feel

1:01:59.200 --> 1:02:01.560
and have with
synthesisers.

1:02:01.600 --> 1:02:03.960
So I play the synthesiser
the same way

1:02:04.000 --> 1:02:08.480
somebody else would
play cello or violin.

1:02:08.520 --> 1:02:12.920
[Majestic melody begins
over the scales]

1:02:12.960 --> 1:02:15.280
- For a classically
trained pianist

1:02:15.320 --> 1:02:17.920
to turn her back
on a keyboard,

1:02:17.960 --> 1:02:19.200
she's crazy.

1:02:19.240 --> 1:02:21.320
It was like learning
a new language

1:02:21.360 --> 1:02:24.200
via the means of cutting
out your own tongue.

1:02:24.240 --> 1:02:25.680
- [Suzanne speaking as
harmonies mimic her voice]:

1:02:25.720 --> 1:02:27.040
Yeah, I can sing
out of tune

1:02:27.080 --> 1:02:28.280
and it'll still be in tune

1:02:28.320 --> 1:02:30.280
because it depends on
what I'm playing.

1:02:30.320 --> 1:02:33.080
This is all the pitch so you
don't have to really be able

1:02:33.120 --> 1:02:35.360
to sing to do this.

1:02:35.400 --> 1:02:37.360
So, it's great.
it's great.

1:02:37.400 --> 1:02:38.240
Hello, hello, hello.

1:02:38.280 --> 1:02:39.360
[Suzanne Narrating]:
I couldn't get a record deal

1:02:39.400 --> 1:02:40.680
because the record companies

1:02:40.720 --> 1:02:45.440
were not interested in a
woman who did not sing.

1:02:45.480 --> 1:02:49.200
Advertising wanted
to be on the edge.

1:02:49.240 --> 1:02:52.240
They were looking for
something different.

1:02:52.280 --> 1:02:54.360
I had total freedom.

1:02:54.400 --> 1:02:57.240
Nobody could tell
me what to do.

1:02:57.280 --> 1:02:58.360
They didn't know what I did.

1:02:58.400 --> 1:03:03.000
[Mysterious chiming music]

1:03:03.200 --> 1:03:07.360
[Electronic squeaky melody]

1:03:07.560 --> 1:03:09.160
- [Male Announcer]: The new
Clairol custom care

1:03:09.200 --> 1:03:10.720
coon brush.

1:03:10.760 --> 1:03:13.520
[Upbeat rock-like music]

1:03:13.560 --> 1:03:14.520
- [Male Announcer]:
Atari is going to

1:03:14.560 --> 1:03:15.560
turn your head around.

1:03:15.600 --> 1:03:16.560
[Exploding sound]

1:03:16.600 --> 1:03:17.960
- [Male Announcer]: Big
news from Covergirl.

1:03:18.000 --> 1:03:20.240
- There's a whole new
thick lash mascara.

1:03:20.280 --> 1:03:24.000
[Liquid pouring with
electronic bubbling sound]

1:03:24.040 --> 1:03:26.160
- The landscape that
she must have walked into

1:03:26.200 --> 1:03:28.160
must have been like
something from Mad Men.

1:03:28.200 --> 1:03:30.160
I remember Suzanne
telling me stories like

1:03:30.200 --> 1:03:32.240
she'd turn up
early to set up

1:03:32.280 --> 1:03:34.240
all the modular
gear in studios

1:03:34.280 --> 1:03:36.520
and a young engineer
would come in and go,

1:03:36.560 --> 1:03:37.720
"Which mic are you
going to sing on?"

1:03:37.760 --> 1:03:39.240
or, "What are you
going to sing for us?"

1:03:39.280 --> 1:03:40.080
Because those
stereotypes were

1:03:40.120 --> 1:03:42.360
so commonplace in
studios in those days.

1:03:42.400 --> 1:03:43.960
[Upbeat rock music]

1:03:44.000 --> 1:03:44.960
- [Suzanne speaking as
chords mirror her voice]:

1:03:45.000 --> 1:03:47.240
Welcome to Xenon.

1:03:47.280 --> 1:03:49.600
- More than anybody else,

1:03:49.640 --> 1:03:55.240
she built a career out of
making weird music,

1:03:55.280 --> 1:03:59.520
which is something I think
everybody aspires to.

1:03:59.560 --> 1:04:01.240
She had her own company.

1:04:01.280 --> 1:04:03.240
She was able to turn
her art into something

1:04:03.280 --> 1:04:04.240
she can live on.

1:04:04.280 --> 1:04:06.520
[Suzanne's sigh is mirrored
by a low electronic echo]

1:04:06.560 --> 1:04:10.160
- [Suzanne with a low and
echoey voice]: Don't be afraid.

1:04:10.200 --> 1:04:14.240
This is my almost male voice.

1:04:14.280 --> 1:04:16.280
[Audience laughs and applauds]

1:04:16.320 --> 1:04:18.240
- Make the thing
make noises for us.

1:04:18.280 --> 1:04:19.000
- Okay, let's-

1:04:19.040 --> 1:04:20.960
- Now first of all, why
do you have this stuff?

1:04:21.000 --> 1:04:21.600
What do you do with this?

1:04:21.640 --> 1:04:23.960
- Well, this is how
I make a living.

1:04:24.000 --> 1:04:27.160
- But I mean, you don't
go door-to-door saying,

1:04:27.200 --> 1:04:29.680
I'll make you sound goofy.

1:04:29.720 --> 1:04:30.280
- Yeah, they call me.
they call me.

1:04:30.320 --> 1:04:33.000
- They call you.

1:04:33.040 --> 1:04:48.240
[Complex wash of
sound slowly ascends]

1:04:48.280 --> 1:04:49.520
- [Suzanne] Should I stop?

1:04:49.560 --> 1:04:52.920
- No, let it go for
about half an hour.

1:04:52.960 --> 1:04:53.200
[Sound stops]

1:04:53.240 --> 1:04:54.280
That's wonderful.

1:04:54.320 --> 1:04:59.240
[Audience applauds]

1:04:59.280 --> 1:05:01.320
- [Suzanne]: It was 1980.

1:05:01.360 --> 1:05:02.480
I was hired to do a
Hollywood feature.

1:05:02.520 --> 1:05:05.080
[Hollow, spinning sound
gets progressively higher]

1:05:05.120 --> 1:05:07.240
It was a Lily Tomlin movie.

1:05:07.280 --> 1:05:11.320
Lily was a woman, the
head of the production

1:05:11.360 --> 1:05:14.040
at Universal was a woman.

1:05:14.080 --> 1:05:16.200
So I had two women
in positions of power.

1:05:16.240 --> 1:05:18.720
And guess what?
I got hired.

1:05:18.760 --> 1:05:20.240
- Is that package for me?

1:05:20.280 --> 1:05:22.720
- Mike, it's for me.

1:05:22.760 --> 1:05:25.160
I didn't know I was
the first woman

1:05:25.200 --> 1:05:29.160
to be hired to score a
major Hollywood feature,

1:05:29.200 --> 1:05:33.360
and I didn't know that
it would be 14 years

1:05:33.400 --> 1:05:35.240
until another
woman was hired.

1:05:35.280 --> 1:05:37.920
[Hollow, spinning sound
gets progressively higher]

1:05:37.960 --> 1:05:42.680
We are casualties of
a day-to-day system

1:05:42.720 --> 1:05:46.200
that operates
without awareness

1:05:46.240 --> 1:05:48.240
that we're even there.

1:05:48.280 --> 1:05:50.240
