1:05:50.280 --> 1:05:56.240
âª Life would go to pieces
without galaxy glue âª

1:05:56.280 --> 1:05:57.680
- [Laurie]: There weren't
any women composers

1:05:57.720 --> 1:05:58.280
that I knew of.

1:05:58.320 --> 1:06:00.000
I had never heard of one.

1:06:00.040 --> 1:06:02.160
[Rapid percussive tones]

1:06:02.200 --> 1:06:06.160
Composers were old
white dead men.

1:06:06.200 --> 1:06:09.160
It was just not something
I ever thought of

1:06:09.200 --> 1:06:12.080
as something I could do.

1:06:12.120 --> 1:06:14.360
When they asked
me in high school,

1:06:14.400 --> 1:06:16.280
"What would you like to
do with your life?"

1:06:16.320 --> 1:06:18.280
I said, "I would
love to do music."

1:06:18.320 --> 1:06:20.200
They said, "Totally
out of the question.

1:06:20.240 --> 1:06:22.440
"You would have needed
to have music lessons

1:06:22.480 --> 1:06:24.520
"all during your childhood."

1:06:24.560 --> 1:06:27.760
So I did a degree
in social sciences,

1:06:27.800 --> 1:06:32.560
but secretly I really always
wanted to do music.

1:06:32.600 --> 1:06:35.560
After I got my bachelor's and
moved to New York,

1:06:35.600 --> 1:06:37.000
I thought, I'm
going to regret it

1:06:37.040 --> 1:06:42.320
for the rest of my life if
I don't give it a real try.

1:06:42.360 --> 1:06:44.560
[Man singing a vocal warm-up]

1:06:44.600 --> 1:06:47.960
I was taking ear training
and music at Juilliard

1:06:48.000 --> 1:06:52.160
and happened to be in
Mike Czajkowski's class.

1:06:52.200 --> 1:06:55.160
And he was working
with Mort Subotnick.

1:06:55.200 --> 1:07:00.160
Mike dragged me down to
Mort's studio and it was like

1:07:00.200 --> 1:07:02.800
music went from black
and white to color.

1:07:02.840 --> 1:07:05.160
[Complex, drone-like
sound expands]

1:07:05.200 --> 1:07:07.160
I fell in love with
electronic music.

1:07:07.200 --> 1:07:09.280
It completely changed the
way I heard everything.

1:07:09.320 --> 1:07:11.560
The sounds of the
traffic in the street

1:07:11.600 --> 1:07:14.200
no longer sounded the same.

1:07:16.600 --> 1:07:19.000
I always wanted to do
something in the arts

1:07:19.040 --> 1:07:22.960
that had to do with the real,
authentic experience

1:07:23.000 --> 1:07:25.520
of being alive,
in contrast to

1:07:25.560 --> 1:07:29.480
the 1950s hypocritical
reality in which I lived,

1:07:29.520 --> 1:07:32.200
in which everything
was glossed over

1:07:32.240 --> 1:07:33.080
with cotton candy.

1:07:33.120 --> 1:07:33.720
[Spoon banging]

1:07:33.760 --> 1:07:36.280
[Upbeat, sweeping
classical music]

1:07:36.320 --> 1:07:38.280
- A perfect dinner Judy.

1:07:38.320 --> 1:07:40.280
And you said she
couldn't boil water

1:07:40.320 --> 1:07:44.680
without burning it.

1:07:44.720 --> 1:07:47.200
- [Laurie]: I got involved in
the downtown art scene,

1:07:47.240 --> 1:07:50.040
which is like "try
anything," you know?

1:07:50.080 --> 1:07:55.280
[Low drone]

1:07:55.320 --> 1:08:00.760
[Mechanical sounds]

1:08:00.800 --> 1:08:05.920
I tackled learning the Buchla
modular analogue system.

1:08:05.960 --> 1:08:08.200
While I could do all kinds of
wonderful things with sounds,

1:08:08.240 --> 1:08:12.960
what I really wanted was the
precision of the computer.

1:08:13.000 --> 1:08:17.560
I got involved with computers
in music out of frustration

1:08:17.600 --> 1:08:20.240
at other ways of
doing music, in part,

1:08:20.280 --> 1:08:23.240
and also because of
the incredible potential

1:08:23.280 --> 1:08:28.240
that they had for combining
the best of all other worlds,

1:08:28.280 --> 1:08:29.320
let's say.

1:08:29.360 --> 1:08:30.720
The memory, the logic,

1:08:30.760 --> 1:08:32.720
the ability to actually
interact with sound

1:08:32.760 --> 1:08:37.360
in real time began
to be possible.

1:08:37.400 --> 1:08:39.720
The complete freedom
to define

1:08:39.760 --> 1:08:42.240
any kind of world you wanted.

1:08:42.280 --> 1:08:49.560
[Warm, fluttering tones]

1:08:49.600 --> 1:08:56.560
[Organ-like notes begin]

1:08:56.600 --> 1:08:57.960
[Fluttering tones fade]

1:08:58.000 --> 1:09:04.840
[A single, spinning
pitch emerges]

1:09:04.880 --> 1:09:11.320
[Organ-like notes flutter]

1:09:11.360 --> 1:09:14.160
[A low, moving
bass tone emerges]

1:09:14.200 --> 1:09:19.280
[It widens into a
splash of sound]

1:09:19.320 --> 1:09:22.360
[Bass tone fades]

1:09:22.400 --> 1:09:35.560
[Penetrating electric tones
sustain and overlap]

1:09:35.600 --> 1:09:40.200
[Bass tone reemerges briefly]

1:09:40.240 --> 1:09:44.720
[Organ-like
fluttering continues]

1:09:44.760 --> 1:09:47.320
[Dissonant splash of tones]

1:09:47.360 --> 1:09:57.360
[Overlapping electric tones
form a friendly melody]

1:09:57.400 --> 1:10:01.960
Computers back then were the
enemy of the counterculture.

1:10:02.000 --> 1:10:04.600
Computers belonged to the
banks and the military

1:10:04.640 --> 1:10:07.240
and the insurance companies.

1:10:07.280 --> 1:10:11.040
Computer music was the utter
dehumanisation of music

1:10:11.080 --> 1:10:13.200
rather than,
to some few of us,

1:10:13.240 --> 1:10:14.520
the liberation of it.

1:10:14.560 --> 1:10:16.520
- Do you mean to tell me
that you haven't heard it?

1:10:16.560 --> 1:10:18.160
- No, I haven't heard it.
I haven't heard it.

1:10:18.200 --> 1:10:19.280
Here, play it.

1:10:19.320 --> 1:10:20.360
- [Woman]: It's really
terrific, Suzie.

1:10:20.400 --> 1:10:21.840
Wait 'til you hear it.

1:10:21.880 --> 1:10:22.280
- [Man]: Excuse me, ladies.

1:10:22.320 --> 1:10:25.280
I have a special request.

1:10:25.320 --> 1:10:42.840
[Upbeat, alternating electronic
beeping tones]

1:10:48.720 --> 1:10:51.960
[Upbeat, alternating electronic
beeping tones]

1:10:52.000 --> 1:10:55.200
- Laurie Spiegel
was a ukulele player

1:10:55.240 --> 1:10:56.960
among other things.

1:10:57.000 --> 1:11:01.280
She had a sense of music
that is based in folk idioms,

1:11:01.320 --> 1:11:03.320
and Appalachian Grove

1:11:03.360 --> 1:11:06.160
is one of the earliest
computer music pieces

1:11:06.200 --> 1:11:08.480
that anyone would want
to listen to [laughs]

1:11:08.520 --> 1:11:11.200
more than once.

1:11:11.240 --> 1:11:13.200
But to think that
it was all done

1:11:13.240 --> 1:11:17.280
by punching holes in cards
and running them

1:11:17.320 --> 1:11:21.920
through the Bell Labs computer
is quite astonishing.

1:11:21.960 --> 1:11:36.280
[Upbeat, alternating electronic
beeping tones continue]

1:11:36.320 --> 1:11:38.840
- [Laurie]: Technology
is just,

1:11:38.880 --> 1:11:40.600
it's a natural
extension of man.

1:11:40.640 --> 1:11:42.600
Man has always
played with tools.

1:11:42.640 --> 1:11:43.480
Man has always
developed tools,

1:11:43.520 --> 1:11:46.080
and it is a tool.

1:11:46.120 --> 1:11:48.360
The machine doesn't
write the music.

1:11:48.400 --> 1:11:50.080
You tell the machine
what to do,

1:11:50.120 --> 1:11:52.080
and the machine is an
extension of you.

1:11:52.120 --> 1:11:56.240
[Phone dialing sounds]

1:11:56.280 --> 1:12:00.280
Bell Labs was a great,
great institution.

1:12:00.320 --> 1:12:05.600
Everything changed after the
AT&T divestiture happened.

1:12:05.640 --> 1:12:07.560
Bell Labs became
product-oriented

1:12:07.600 --> 1:12:09.240
instead of pure research.

1:12:09.280 --> 1:12:13.320
[Faint phone conversations
and dialing]

1:12:13.360 --> 1:12:16.280
After I left there,
I was absolutely desolate.

1:12:16.320 --> 1:12:23.160
I had lost my main
creative medium.

1:12:23.200 --> 1:12:24.840
- [Male Interviewer]:
Laurie Spiegel,

1:12:24.880 --> 1:12:27.240
you have a very
fascinating new product,

1:12:27.280 --> 1:12:29.160
a software program,
which you created...

1:12:29.200 --> 1:12:31.160
- Yeah.
- ...called Music Mouse.

1:12:31.200 --> 1:12:32.880
Can you tell us a little
bit about that?

1:12:33.120 --> 1:12:36.000
- This is actually a program
which turns the Macintosh

1:12:36.040 --> 1:12:38.000
into an instrument
which you play,

1:12:38.040 --> 1:12:41.960
and unlike traditional
instruments,

1:12:42.000 --> 1:12:44.160
on the other hand,
it uses the logic

1:12:44.200 --> 1:12:48.240
of the computer supportively
to musical expression.

1:12:48.280 --> 1:12:50.720
[Uplifting piano music]

1:12:50.760 --> 1:12:55.240
[Melody rises and falls
with the horizontal line]

1:12:55.280 --> 1:12:57.800
[Piano chords follow
the vertical lines]

1:12:57.840 --> 1:12:59.440
I needed an instrument.

1:12:59.480 --> 1:13:02.520
I wanted something which was
entirely under my own control

1:13:02.560 --> 1:13:04.200
that didn't have
to be marketable

1:13:04.240 --> 1:13:06.160
or it didn't involve funding.

1:13:06.200 --> 1:13:08.800
It was just something
entirely mine.

1:13:08.840 --> 1:13:14.800
[Melody and chords ascend]

1:13:14.880 --> 1:13:16.040
It's the first time
I've done something

1:13:16.080 --> 1:13:17.040
essentially for myself

1:13:17.080 --> 1:13:18.240
that I'm just really
making available

1:13:18.280 --> 1:13:19.320
to anybody who wants it,

1:13:19.360 --> 1:13:21.200
and I hope a lot
of people really get

1:13:21.240 --> 1:13:22.320
a lot of good
music out of it.

1:13:22.360 --> 1:13:24.720
Everybody who's using it
seems to be doing

1:13:24.760 --> 1:13:25.680
something slightly different.

1:13:25.720 --> 1:13:27.040
So I'll be interested,
you know,

1:13:27.080 --> 1:13:29.680
keeping my ears open
for whatever you do.

1:13:29.720 --> 1:13:31.040
Mouse ears.

1:13:31.080 --> 1:13:34.720
[Chords ascend then
rapidly descend]

1:13:34.760 --> 1:13:37.080
[Sustained notes form a
warm blanket of sound]

1:13:37.120 --> 1:13:40.280
[A new piece begins with
dissonant, moving notes]

1:13:40.320 --> 1:13:41.760
- She wasn't satisfied with

1:13:41.800 --> 1:13:44.200
the given constraints of
what she was working with.

1:13:44.240 --> 1:13:46.680
So she decided to make
her own software.

1:13:46.720 --> 1:13:50.760
She just embodies
this idea of agency.

1:13:50.800 --> 1:13:52.280
[The piece continues]

1:13:52.320 --> 1:13:56.440
[Each note has both lower tone
and a higher, harsh tone]

1:13:56.480 --> 1:13:59.160
- Her work was very
much in the lineage

1:13:59.200 --> 1:14:00.320
with the work of Daphne Oram

1:14:00.360 --> 1:14:02.840
because of her engineering

1:14:02.880 --> 1:14:06.240
of a new language
for producing sounds,

1:14:06.280 --> 1:14:08.360
and the support system
for other people

1:14:08.400 --> 1:14:10.360
to invent new soundscapes.

1:14:10.400 --> 1:14:16.200
[Irregular melody]

1:14:16.240 --> 1:14:18.000
- [Female Interviewer]: What's
the most exciting thing

1:14:18.040 --> 1:14:20.360
about the field for you?

1:14:20.400 --> 1:14:25.760
- Well, this is a time at
which many people feel

1:14:25.800 --> 1:14:29.080
that there are a lot of
dead ends in music,

1:14:29.120 --> 1:14:30.240
that there isn't
a lot more to do.

1:14:30.280 --> 1:14:31.040
This is actually...

1:14:31.080 --> 1:14:34.040
I see this and through
the technology,

1:14:34.080 --> 1:14:36.240
I experience this as
quite the opposite.

1:14:36.280 --> 1:14:40.800
This is a period in which we
realise we've only just begun

1:14:40.840 --> 1:14:44.320
to scratch the surface of
what's possible musically.

1:14:44.360 --> 1:14:51.280
[Energetic, alternating,
percussive tones]

1:14:51.320 --> 1:14:52.760
- [Female Narrator]:
Through technology,

1:14:52.800 --> 1:14:57.280
voices are amplified,
silence is broken,

1:14:57.320 --> 1:14:59.840
spaces are shared.

1:14:59.880 --> 1:15:02.280
The music in our head

1:15:02.320 --> 1:15:05.920
can finally be
heard by others.

1:15:05.960 --> 1:15:11.240
[Pigeons cooing]

1:15:11.280 --> 1:15:21.520
[Sparrows chirping]

1:15:21.560 --> 1:15:27.200
[Wings flapping]

1:15:27.240 --> 1:15:29.160
- [Laurie]: We
were, in a way,

1:15:29.200 --> 1:15:31.480
trying to make a
bit of a revolution,

1:15:31.520 --> 1:15:33.280
but I don't think we
would have put it

1:15:33.320 --> 1:15:34.240
in such grandiose terms.

1:15:34.280 --> 1:15:39.040
We were trying to put music
back in touch with itself.

1:15:40.320 --> 1:15:45.240
[Relaxed, low-pitched
electronic groove]

1:15:45.280 --> 1:15:49.240
[Buttons clicking]

1:15:49.280 --> 1:15:52.520
- [Suzanne whispering]: Okay,
and this has to go here.

1:15:52.560 --> 1:15:53.840
This is here.

1:15:53.880 --> 1:15:55.280
This is...

1:15:59.240 --> 1:16:06.320
[Buttons clicking rapidly]

1:16:06.360 --> 1:16:13.760
[Robotic beeping]

1:16:13.800 --> 1:16:18.440
There were really no role
models for female composers

1:16:18.480 --> 1:16:21.920
when I studied music.

1:16:21.960 --> 1:16:26.520
Overall, we are incrementally
getting more visibility,

1:16:26.560 --> 1:16:30.320
but it's two steps forward
and one step back.

1:16:32.200 --> 1:16:34.520
And to this day
it kind of irks me

1:16:34.560 --> 1:16:38.040
that when I turn on my
favorite radio station,

1:16:38.080 --> 1:16:40.680
it's just the male parade.

1:16:40.720 --> 1:16:45.200
[Low tones move over an
orchestra of electronic sounds]

1:16:45.240 --> 1:16:51.920
[Sounds get choppier,
resembling radio tuning]

1:16:51.960 --> 1:16:55.360
[Low drone with
a sustained pitch]

1:16:56.000 --> 1:16:59.320
- [Laurie]: It is odd that
electronic music,

1:16:59.360 --> 1:17:03.920
it's generally considered
a man's field.

1:17:03.960 --> 1:17:08.200
Women have been
so formative in it.

1:17:08.240 --> 1:17:17.960
[Low drone continues]

1:17:18.000 --> 1:17:18.840
- [Pauline]: There has to be

1:17:18.880 --> 1:17:20.160
a complete change of
consciousness

1:17:20.200 --> 1:17:23.200
throughout the
musical field,

1:17:23.240 --> 1:17:25.480
where they could begin to
teach music that's written

1:17:25.520 --> 1:17:30.800
by women, as well as men,
as well as of all colours,

